# User acceptance before commit — MyConciergeHotel.com

Audit 2026-05-26 — the agent shipped Sprints 1-5 of Le Concierge Club
(5 new public pages, 2 agent endpoints, ~50 files changed), committed,
pushed, and reported "it's live". The PO landed on the homepage and
saw **nothing**: no link in the nav, no hero strip, no entry in the
footer. The work was technically deployed and functionally invisible.

This rule exists so it never happens again.

## The hard rule

> **Before `git commit`, `git push`, or saying "it's deployed", the
> agent MUST walk the change as a real user would and verify it is
> visible from the entry points a real user would use.**

Hand-waving ("the page exists at this URL") is not acceptance. Reading
your own diff is not acceptance. Running unit tests is not acceptance.
The only acceptable evidence is: **you reached the change by clicking
through the site like a human, and you can prove it (screenshot or
browser snapshot in the chat).**

## When this rule applies

Mandatory for any change that:

- Adds a new public route (`/le-concierge-club`, `/itineraires/<slug>`, …).
- Adds or modifies a UI block on an existing route (hero strip, banner,
  CTA, mega-menu entry, footer column, dashboard card).
- Adds or modifies a form, button, link, or interactive element.
- Adds copy that the user sees (i18n keys, AEO blocks, FAQ entries,
  ConciergeAdvice, factual summary).
- Changes JSON-LD shape, canonical, hreflang, robots, sitemap entries
  (verify via the live page source + `view-source:` or curl).

**NOT** mandatory (skip the user walk-through, normal unit/typecheck
discipline is enough):

- Pure refactor with zero user-visible delta (rename a function,
  re-organise a domain package, etc.).
- Migrations / DB schema / RLS that don't change any rendered UI yet.
- Vendor adapter, integration package, or LLM pipeline that is not
  wired into a public route.
- CI / build / tooling changes.
- Documentation (markdown, ADRs, skills).

When in doubt: **walk it**.

## The walk-through checklist

1. **List the entry points** — name the URLs a real user would actually
   land on to see your change. Examples:
   - Homepage `/` and `/en`
   - Hotel fiche `/hotel/<test-slug>` (use the canonical test fiche
     `/hotel/le-meurice` or any of the 443 published hotels).
   - The new route itself (`/le-concierge-club`).
   - The dashboard `/compte` (if signed-in change).
2. **Build the app locally OR rely on the latest Vercel preview** —
   `pnpm dev` from `apps/web` for fast iteration, or pull the preview
   URL of the current branch from `vercel ls` / the PR check.
3. **Walk through every entry point** using the `cursor-ide-browser`
   MCP (skill `user-acceptance-loop`) OR the `browser-use` subagent:
   - `browser_navigate` to the entry URL.
   - `browser_snapshot` (cheap, accessibility tree) — confirm the new
     copy / link / block is in the DOM.
   - `browser_take_screenshot` — attach the visual proof. The agent
     looks at it and confirms the change is **visually obvious** at
     first glance (not buried 3 scrolls down with no contrast).
4. **Test the discoverability path** — start from the homepage and
   click your way to the change. If you can't reach it in ≤ 2 clicks
   without knowing the URL, the change is invisible — fix the nav,
   footer, or homepage strip BEFORE committing.
5. **Test both locales** when the change ships in fr + en.
6. **Mobile + desktop snapshot** when the change touches layout — the
   mobile-nav is a separate component (`apps/web/src/components/
   layout/mobile-nav.tsx`); a desktop-only check misses ~30 % of
   sessions (GA4 baseline).
7. **Test the failure mode** — what happens if Supabase / Algolia /
   Cloudinary is unavailable? The page must not 500. Skill `nextjs-
   app-router` §Data fetching covers the defensive-fallback pattern.

## When the local dev server can't run (no env, no Supabase, etc.)

The walk-through still applies — use the live preview / production URL.
Two paths:

- **Vercel preview URL** for the current branch: pull it via
  `vercel ls --token=$VERCEL_TOKEN` or the GitHub PR check, then walk
  the preview with the browser MCP. This is the canonical path for
  catalogue / SEO changes (no localhost mocks can ever match the real
  Supabase row counts).
- **Production URL** for changes that landed in a previous commit but
  weren't surfaced — the agent walks `https://myconciergehotel.com/...`
  as a real user, screenshots the gap, then fixes it in a follow-up
  commit. **This is exactly what 2026-05-26 demanded** — the pages
  existed in prod, the nav didn't reference them.

## What the agent reports to the user

After the walk-through, the agent's message MUST include:

- The exact URLs walked (with locale).
- A 1-line summary of what is visible at each URL.
- The discoverability proof: "starting from `/`, the user reaches
  the change via `<menu name> > <link name>` (1 click)".
- The screenshots taken (the IDE renders them inline).
- The known gaps left unfixed (if any) — explicit, not implicit.

A commit message MAY reference the walk-through with a `Tested:` line:

```
Tested: walked /fr/, /fr/le-concierge-club, /en/le-concierge-club via
  browser MCP. Confirmed nav entries in Concierge mega-menu and home
  ribbon are visible above the fold on desktop + mobile.
```

## Anti-patterns to refuse

| Anti-pattern | Why it fails | Correct path |
| --- | --- | --- |
| "The route exists at `/le-concierge-club`, so it's live." | A URL existing ≠ a user finding it. | Walk from `/` and confirm the click path. |
| "Tests pass, lint passes, typecheck passes — shipping." | Tests check correctness, not visibility. | Add the browser walk-through. |
| Pushing a hero banner without ever loading the page that hosts it. | LCP regressions and dark patterns slip in silently. | Screenshot above-the-fold render. |
| Adding a form server-action without filling the form in a real browser. | Honeypot / Zod / CSRF traps the form silently. | Submit the form once end-to-end. |
| Adding a new nav entry without checking the mobile burger menu. | Mobile-nav is a separate component; entries can desync. | Open the burger on mobile viewport. |
| "I trust the E2E tests in CI." | CI Playwright tests run a curated set of paths and rarely catch a missing nav entry on a NEW route. | Walk it once manually; add a Playwright case if it warrants regression coverage. |

## Tooling reference

- **Browser walk-through** — `mcp_cursor-ide-browser` (browser_navigate,
  browser_snapshot, browser_take_screenshot, browser_click, browser_type).
- **Hands-off long sequences** — `browser-use` subagent.
- **Live preview lookup** — `mcp_plugin-vercel-vercel` (list_deployments,
  get_deployment).
- **E2E regression** — `apps/web/e2e/<journey>.spec.ts` (skill `e2e-
  testing`).

See `.cursor/skills/user-acceptance-loop/SKILL.md` for the concrete
recipes (browser MCP cheat-sheet, sample walk-through prompts for the
`browser-use` subagent, scoring rubric for "is the change visible").

## Reference cases

- **2026-05-26 — Concierge Club invisibility**: commit
  `af4dc50 feat(club): Le Concierge Club programme — Sprints 1 → 5`
  shipped 5 pages + 2 endpoints with zero nav surfacing. Required a
  follow-up commit `87caf8b` to add header + footer + mobile + home
  ribbon entries. The original PR should have failed acceptance.
